<dl id="n08071g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08071g">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08071g"> 71(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Christtide</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The influence of Puritans, though not strong enough to proscribe such words as <i>Christmas</i>, for which they wanted to substitute <i>Christtide</i> in order to avoid the Catholic <i>mass</i>, was yet strong enough to modify the custom of swearing. <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 236-7</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
